1
00:02:47,001 --> 00:02:48,294
Starling!

2
00:02:50,588 --> 00:02:51,798
Starling!

3
00:02:54,842 --> 00:02:57,512
Crawford wants to see you in his office.

4
00:02:57,929 --> 00:02:59,347
Thank you, sir.

5
00:03:47,353 --> 00:03:48,771
- Clarice.
- Hey.

6
00:04:37,445 --> 00:04:39,530
...so there shouldn't be any problem
if you could...

7
00:04:39,655 --> 00:04:41,175
- You looking for Crawford?
- Yes, sir.

8
00:04:41,240 --> 00:04:43,886
He should be back in a couple minutes.
Why don't you wait in his office?

9
00:04:43,910 --> 00:04:46,871
- Okay.
- And I think they were over in Flushing...

10
00:05:41,509 --> 00:05:42,802
Starling,

11
00:05:43,678 --> 00:05:45,763
Clarice M. Good morning.

12
00:05:45,930 --> 00:05:47,223
Good morning, Mr. Crawford.

13
00:05:47,390 --> 00:05:50,643
Sorry to pull you off of the course
at such short notice.

14
00:05:50,810 --> 00:05:52,645
Your instructors tell
me you're doing well.

15
00:05:52,812 --> 00:05:54,689
- Top quarter of your class.
- I hope so.

16
00:05:54,856 --> 00:05:57,316
They haven't posted any grades yet.

17
00:05:57,567 --> 00:06:00,069
A job's come up, and I thought about you.

18
00:06:00,236 --> 00:06:03,072
Not a job, really.
More of an interesting errand.

19
00:06:03,239 --> 00:06:04,407
Sit down.

20
00:06:04,866 --> 00:06:06,075
Yes, sir.

21
00:06:06,701 --> 00:06:10,121
I remember you from my seminar at UVA.

22
00:06:11,205 --> 00:06:13,082
You grilled me pretty hard, as I recall,

23
00:06:13,249 --> 00:06:15,668
on the Bureau's civil rights record
in the Hoover years.

24
00:06:15,835 --> 00:06:17,044
I gave you an "A."

25
00:06:17,211 --> 00:06:18,588
A-minus, sir.

26
00:06:21,048 --> 00:06:24,510
Let's see. Double major,
psych and criminology. Graduated magna.

27
00:06:24,635 --> 00:06:27,263
Summer internships
at the Reitzinger Clinic.

28
00:06:27,430 --> 00:06:29,223
It says here when you graduate,

29
00:06:29,390 --> 00:06:32,351
you want to come to work for me
in Behavioral Science.

30
00:06:32,518 --> 00:06:34,604
Yes, very much, sir. Very much.

31
00:06:36,022 --> 00:06:38,691
We're interviewing all the serial killers
now in custody

32
00:06:38,858 --> 00:06:40,860
for a psycho-behavioral profile.

33
00:06:41,027 --> 00:06:43,613
It could be a real help in unsolved cases.

34
00:06:43,779 --> 00:06:46,574
Most of them have been
happy to talk to us.

35
00:06:46,741 --> 00:06:48,910
Do you spook easily, Starling?

36
00:06:49,160 --> 00:06:50,578
Not yet, sir.

37
00:06:50,995 --> 00:06:53,706
See, the one we want most,
refuses to cooperate.

38
00:06:53,873 --> 00:06:56,584
I want you to go after him again today
in the asylum.

39
00:06:56,751 --> 00:06:58,294
And who's the subject?

40
00:06:58,461 --> 00:07:00,713
The psychiatrist Hannibal Lecter.

41
00:07:00,963 --> 00:07:02,798
Hannibal the Cannibal.

42
00:07:03,341 --> 00:07:05,801
I don't expect him to talk to you,

43
00:07:07,345 --> 00:07:09,972
but I have to be able to say we tried.

44
00:07:10,139 --> 00:07:13,017
So if he won't cooperate,
I want just straight reporting.

45
00:07:13,184 --> 00:07:15,144
How's he look? How's his cell look?

46
00:07:15,311 --> 00:07:16,812
Is he sketching, drawing?

47
00:07:16,979 --> 00:07:19,190
If he is, what's he sketching?

48
00:07:22,526 --> 00:07:24,946
Here's a dossier on Lecter.

49
00:07:27,490 --> 00:07:30,868
A copy of our questionnaire
and a special ID for you.

50
00:07:31,118 --> 00:07:33,829
Have your memo on my desk
by 0800 Wednesday.

51
00:07:33,996 --> 00:07:35,122
Okay.

52
00:07:37,583 --> 00:07:40,670
Excuse me, sir, but why the urgency?

53
00:07:40,836 --> 00:07:42,713
Lecter's been in prison
for so many years now.

54
00:07:42,880 --> 00:07:45,967
Is there some connection
between him and Buffalo Bill maybe?

55
00:07:46,133 --> 00:07:47,718
I wish there were.

56
00:07:48,052 --> 00:07:51,806
- I want your full attention, Starling.
- Yes, sir.

57
00:07:52,014 --> 00:07:54,642
Be very careful with Hannibal Lecter.

58
00:07:55,059 --> 00:07:56,435
Dr. Chilton at the asylum

59
00:07:56,602 --> 00:07:59,689
will go over all the physical procedures
used with him.

60
00:07:59,855 --> 00:08:03,067
Do not deviate from them
for any reason whatsoever,

61
00:08:03,484 --> 00:08:06,070
and you're to tell him
nothing personal, Starling.

62
00:08:06,237 --> 00:08:09,740
Believe me, you don't want
Hannibal Lecter inside your head.

63
00:08:09,865 --> 00:08:12,827
Just do your job,
but never forget what he is.

64
00:08:12,994 --> 00:08:14,161
And what is that?

65
00:08:14,620 --> 00:08:16,330
{\an8}Oh, he's a monster.

66
00:08:16,831 --> 00:08:18,332
{\an8}A pure psychopath.

67
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,168
So rare to capture one alive.

68
00:08:21,335 --> 00:08:25,172
From a research point of view,
Lecter is our most prized asset.

69
00:08:26,716 --> 00:08:27,842
Well.

70
00:08:29,677 --> 00:08:32,054
You know, we get a lot of detectives here,
but I must say,

71
00:08:32,221 --> 00:08:34,807
I can't ever remember one as attractive.

72
00:08:36,851 --> 00:08:39,478
Will you be in Baltimore overnight?

73
00:08:39,895 --> 00:08:43,858
Because this can be quite a fun town
if you have the right guide.

74
00:08:45,109 --> 00:08:47,611
Well, I'm sure
this is a great town, Dr. Chilton,

75
00:08:47,778 --> 00:08:52,575
but my instructions are to talk to
Dr. Lecter and report back this afternoon.

76
00:08:52,950 --> 00:08:54,118
{\an8}I see.

77
00:08:55,119 --> 00:08:56,412
{\an8}Let's make this quick, then.

78
00:08:56,620 --> 00:08:58,247
We've tried to study him, of course,

79
00:08:58,414 --> 00:09:01,208
but he's much too sophisticated
for the standard tests.

80
00:09:01,375 --> 00:09:03,627
Oh, my, does he hate us!

81
00:09:03,794 --> 00:09:05,796
He thinks I'm his nemesis.

82
00:09:07,339 --> 00:09:10,217
Crawford's very clever, isn't he?
Using you.

83
00:09:10,384 --> 00:09:11,635
What do you mean, sir?

84
00:09:11,802 --> 00:09:14,513
A pretty young woman to turn him on.

85
00:09:15,097 --> 00:09:17,808
I don't believe Lecter's even seen a woman
in eight years.

86
00:09:17,975 --> 00:09:20,186
And, oh, are you ever his taste.

87
00:09:20,436 --> 00:09:21,771
So to speak.

88
00:09:21,937 --> 00:09:24,982
I graduated from UVA, Doctor.
It is not a charm school.

89
00:09:25,149 --> 00:09:28,360
Good. Then you should be able
to remember the rules.

90
00:09:31,238 --> 00:09:33,574
Do not touch the glass.
Do not approach the glass.

91
00:09:33,741 --> 00:09:36,994
You pass him nothing but soft paper.
No pencils or pens.

92
00:09:37,161 --> 00:09:39,205
No staples or paper clips on his paper.

93
00:09:39,371 --> 00:09:41,624
Use the sliding food carrier.
No exceptions.

94
00:09:41,791 --> 00:09:44,126
If he attempts to pass you anything,
do not accept it.

95
00:09:44,293 --> 00:09:47,129
- Do you understand me?
- Yes, I understand, sir.

96
00:09:48,130 --> 00:09:51,383
I'm going to show you
why we insist on such precautions.

97
00:09:51,509 --> 00:09:54,095
On the afternoon of July 8, 1981,

98
00:09:54,261 --> 00:09:57,098
he complained of chest pains
and was taken to the dispensary.

99
00:09:57,264 --> 00:09:59,850
His mouthpiece and restraints
were removed for an EKG.

100
00:10:00,017 --> 00:10:02,853
When the nurse leaned over him,
he did this to her.

101
00:10:05,648 --> 00:10:08,818
The doctors managed to reset her jaw,
more or less,

102
00:10:08,984 --> 00:10:10,361
save one of her eyes.

103
00:10:10,528 --> 00:10:12,738
His pulse never got above 85,

104
00:10:13,280 --> 00:10:15,157
even when he ate her tongue.

105
00:10:15,991 --> 00:10:17,868
I keep him in here.

106
00:10:18,119 --> 00:10:19,453
Dr. Chilton.

107
00:10:22,248 --> 00:10:24,291
If Lecter feels that you're his enemy,

108
00:10:24,458 --> 00:10:28,129
then, well, maybe we'll have more luck
if I go in by myself.

109
00:10:28,295 --> 00:10:29,922
What do you think?

110
00:10:32,675 --> 00:10:36,637
You might have suggested this
in my office and saved me the time.

111
00:10:37,805 --> 00:10:42,184
Yes, sir, but then I would have missed
the pleasure of your company, sir.

112
00:10:45,062 --> 00:10:47,481
When she's finished, bring her out.

113
00:11:15,801 --> 00:11:17,344
Hi. I'm Barney.

114
00:11:17,845 --> 00:11:20,389
He told you, don't get near the glass?

115
00:11:20,848 --> 00:11:22,933
Yes, he did. Clarice Starling.

116
00:11:23,517 --> 00:11:24,935
Nice to meet you, Clarice.

117
00:11:25,060 --> 00:11:27,479
You can hang your
coat up here if you like.

118
00:11:27,646 --> 00:11:29,231
Thank you. I will.

119
00:11:31,150 --> 00:11:33,611
He's past the others. The last cell.

120
00:11:33,777 --> 00:11:35,571
You keep to the right.

121
00:11:38,032 --> 00:11:39,742
I put out a chair for you.

122
00:11:39,909 --> 00:11:42,369
Oh, yes. That's very good. Thank you.

123
00:11:43,329 --> 00:11:46,415
I'll be watching. You'll do fine.

124
00:11:57,092 --> 00:11:58,385
Hi.

125
00:12:17,404 --> 00:12:19,365
I can smell your cunt.

126
00:12:32,962 --> 00:12:34,380
Good morning.

127
00:12:34,672 --> 00:12:38,425
Dr. Lecter, my name is Clarice Starling.
May I speak with you?

128
00:12:38,842 --> 00:12:41,470
You're one of Jack Crawford's, aren't you?

129
00:12:41,637 --> 00:12:42,930
I am, yes, sir.

130
00:12:43,931 --> 00:12:46,058
May I see your credentials?

131
00:12:46,475 --> 00:12:47,768
Certainly.

132
00:12:54,817 --> 00:12:56,360
Closer, please.

133
00:12:58,279 --> 00:12:59,905
Closer.

134
00:13:15,796 --> 00:13:17,715
That expires in one week.

135
00:13:17,965 --> 00:13:20,467
You're not real FBI, are you?

136
00:13:20,801 --> 00:13:23,304
I'm still in training at the Academy.

137
00:13:24,471 --> 00:13:26,974
Jack Crawford sent a trainee to me?

138
00:13:27,683 --> 00:13:29,393
Yes. I'm a student.

139
00:13:29,643 --> 00:13:31,687
I'm here to learn from you.

140
00:13:31,854 --> 00:13:33,174
Maybe you can decide for yourself

141
00:13:33,272 --> 00:13:36,317
whether or not I'm qualified enough
to do that.

142
00:13:38,444 --> 00:13:41,530
That is rather slippery of you,
Agent Starling.

143
00:13:45,159 --> 00:13:46,785
Sit, please.

144
00:13:54,209 --> 00:13:55,919
Now, then. Tell me,

145
00:13:56,045 --> 00:13:58,255
what did Miggs say to you?

146
00:13:58,422 --> 00:14:00,841
Multiple Miggs in the next cell.

147
00:14:01,175 --> 00:14:02,760
He hissed at you.

148
00:14:02,926 --> 00:14:04,470
What did he say?

149
00:14:05,721 --> 00:14:08,557
He said, "I can smell your cunt."

150
00:14:08,974 --> 00:14:10,142
I see.

151
00:14:11,602 --> 00:14:13,395
I myself cannot.

152
00:14:22,613 --> 00:14:25,074
You use Evyan skin cream.

153
00:14:27,868 --> 00:14:30,621
And sometimes you wear L'Air du Temps,

154
00:14:32,122 --> 00:14:33,540
but not today.

155
00:14:35,918 --> 00:14:38,212
Did you do all these drawings, Doctor?

156
00:14:40,839 --> 00:14:44,009
That is the Duomo,
seen from the Belvedere.

157
00:14:45,552 --> 00:14:47,096
You know Florence?

158
00:14:48,222 --> 00:14:50,391
All that detail just from memory, sir?

159
00:14:50,557 --> 00:14:54,353
Memory, Agent Starling,
is what I have instead of a view.

160
00:14:54,520 --> 00:14:55,604
Well,

161
00:14:55,771 --> 00:15:00,484
perhaps you'd care to lend us your view
on this questionnaire, sir.

162
00:15:00,651 --> 00:15:02,986
Oh, no, no, no.

163
00:15:03,320 --> 00:15:05,030
You were doing fine.

164
00:15:05,197 --> 00:15:08,283
You had been courteous
and receptive to courtesy.

165
00:15:08,450 --> 00:15:12,955
You had established trust
with the embarrassing truth about Miggs.

166
00:15:13,122 --> 00:15:17,251
And now this ham-handed segue
into your questionnaire.

167
00:15:18,919 --> 00:15:20,337
It won't do.

168
00:15:20,629 --> 00:15:22,548
I'm only asking you to look at this,
Doctor.

169
00:15:22,714 --> 00:15:24,716
Either you will or you won't.

170
00:15:24,883 --> 00:15:25,926
Yeah.

171
00:15:26,593 --> 00:15:28,637
Jack Crawford must be very busy indeed,

172
00:15:28,804 --> 00:15:31,557
if he is recruiting help
from the student body.

173
00:15:31,723 --> 00:15:34,435
Busy hunting that new one, Buffalo Bill.

174
00:15:34,601 --> 00:15:36,645
What a naughty boy he is.

175
00:15:37,187 --> 00:15:40,524
Do you know why he's called Buffalo Bill?

176
00:15:40,691 --> 00:15:43,819
Please tell me. The newspapers won't say.

177
00:15:45,112 --> 00:15:47,739
Well, it started as a bad joke
in Kansas City Homicide.

178
00:15:47,906 --> 00:15:51,618
They said,
"This one likes to skin his humps."

179
00:15:53,162 --> 00:15:57,040
Why do you think he removes their skins,

180
00:15:57,207 --> 00:15:58,625
Agent Starling?

181
00:15:58,792 --> 00:16:00,961
Enthrall me with your acumen.

182
00:16:01,712 --> 00:16:03,255
It excites him.

183
00:16:03,589 --> 00:16:07,259
Most serial killers keep
some sort of trophies from their victims.

184
00:16:07,426 --> 00:16:08,677
I didn't.

185
00:16:08,844 --> 00:16:09,887
No.

186
00:16:10,053 --> 00:16:11,638
No, you ate yours.

187
00:16:14,224 --> 00:16:16,268
You send that through now.

188
00:16:43,295 --> 00:16:44,254
Oh, Agent Starling,

189
00:16:44,421 --> 00:16:47,883
you think you can dissect me
with this blunt, little tool?

190
00:16:48,467 --> 00:16:49,510
No.

191
00:16:49,885 --> 00:16:51,428
I thought that your knowledge...

192
00:16:51,595 --> 00:16:53,805
You're so ambitious, aren't you?

193
00:16:54,181 --> 00:16:55,501
You know what you look like to me

194
00:16:55,557 --> 00:16:57,893
with your good bag and your cheap shoes?

195
00:16:58,060 --> 00:16:59,770
You look like a rube.

196
00:17:00,103 --> 00:17:04,191
A well-scrubbed, hustling rube
with a little taste.

197
00:17:05,025 --> 00:17:07,402
Good nutrition has given you
some length of bone,

198
00:17:07,569 --> 00:17:10,781
but you're not more than one generation
from poor white trash,

199
00:17:10,948 --> 00:17:12,824
are you, Agent Starling?

200
00:17:12,991 --> 00:17:15,702
And that accent you've tried
so desperately to shed,

201
00:17:15,869 --> 00:17:17,538
pure West Virginia.

202
00:17:18,080 --> 00:17:20,332
What does your father do?
Is he a coal miner?

203
00:17:20,499 --> 00:17:22,417
Does he stink of the lamp?

204
00:17:22,584 --> 00:17:25,170
And, oh, how quickly the boys found you.

205
00:17:25,295 --> 00:17:28,757
All those tedious, sticky fumblings
in the back seats of cars,

206
00:17:28,924 --> 00:17:32,594
while you could only dream
of getting out, getting anywhere,

207
00:17:32,761 --> 00:17:36,431
getting all the way to the FBI.

208
00:17:39,726 --> 00:17:41,603
You see a lot, Doctor.

209
00:17:42,563 --> 00:17:47,526
But are you strong enough to point
that high-powered perception at yourself?

210
00:17:48,735 --> 00:17:50,028
What about it? Why don't you...

211
00:17:50,195 --> 00:17:53,740
Why don't you look at yourself
and write down what you see?

212
00:17:54,616 --> 00:17:56,410
Maybe you're afraid to.

213
00:18:06,003 --> 00:18:08,755
A census-taker once tried to test me.

214
00:18:09,089 --> 00:18:12,467
I ate his liver with some fava beans,

215
00:18:12,634 --> 00:18:14,636
and a nice Chianti.

216
00:18:23,604 --> 00:18:26,398
You fly back to school now,
little Starling.

217
00:18:27,024 --> 00:18:28,567
Fly, fly, fly.

218
00:18:43,624 --> 00:18:47,336
I bit my wrist so I could die.

219
00:18:49,046 --> 00:18:50,672
Look at the blood!

220
00:18:51,256 --> 00:18:52,424
Gotcha!

221
00:18:52,966 --> 00:18:55,510
Miggs! You stupid fuck!

222
00:18:57,929 --> 00:18:59,431
Hannibal the Cannibal!

223
00:18:59,598 --> 00:19:01,099
Agent Starling! Come back!

224
00:19:01,266 --> 00:19:03,477
Agent Starling! Agent Starling!

225
00:19:03,727 --> 00:19:05,246
I would not have had that happen to you.

226
00:19:05,270 --> 00:19:06,938
Discourtesy is unspeakably ugly to me.

227
00:19:07,105 --> 00:19:09,650
- Then do this test for me.
- No, but I will make you happy.

228
00:19:09,816 --> 00:19:11,616
I'll give you a chance
for what you love most.

229
00:19:11,735 --> 00:19:13,713
- And what is that, Doctor?
- Advancement, of course.

230
00:19:13,737 --> 00:19:17,282
Now listen carefully. Look deep
within yourself, Clarice Starling.

231
00:19:17,449 --> 00:19:21,244
Go seek out Miss Mofet,
an old patient of mine. M-o-f-e-t. Go now.

232
00:19:21,411 --> 00:19:22,329
Doctor.

233
00:19:22,496 --> 00:19:23,931
I don't think Miggs could manage again
quite so soon,

234
00:19:23,955 --> 00:19:25,123
even though he is crazy.

235
00:19:25,290 --> 00:19:26,541
Go now!

236
00:20:08,333 --> 00:20:09,626
Hey, Bill.

237
00:20:13,213 --> 00:20:14,256
Hey.

238
00:20:14,423 --> 00:20:16,508
- Daddy!
- Hey, Clarice.

239
00:20:18,051 --> 00:20:19,386
How are you?

240
00:20:20,303 --> 00:20:22,264
Did you get any bad guys today, Daddy?

241
00:20:22,431 --> 00:20:25,392
- No, angel, they all got away.
- Aw, shoot.

242
00:20:45,912 --> 00:20:48,206
FBI! Hands up! Don't move!

243
00:20:48,373 --> 00:20:49,458
Turn around!

244
00:20:49,624 --> 00:20:51,918
Hands behind your back! Thumbs up.

245
00:20:55,672 --> 00:20:57,507
You're dead, Starling.

246
00:20:58,258 --> 00:21:00,969
Johnson, good job.
Good entry. Good commands.

247
00:21:01,136 --> 00:21:03,281
- Starling, where's your danger area?
- In the corner, sir.

248
00:21:03,305 --> 00:21:04,699
- Did you check the corner?
- No, sir.

249
00:21:04,723 --> 00:21:05,923
That's the reason you're dead.

250
00:21:06,183 --> 00:21:07,726
3109.

251
00:21:08,101 --> 00:21:09,144
3109.

252
00:21:09,311 --> 00:21:13,482
Breaking doors or windows
to enter or exit.

253
00:21:14,608 --> 00:21:15,984
Rule 404...

254
00:21:34,878 --> 00:21:37,714
- Clarice, phone. It's the guru.
- Crawford?

255
00:21:37,881 --> 00:21:39,132
- Yeah.
- Thanks, Ardelia.

256
00:21:39,466 --> 00:21:41,134
- Starling?
<i>- Sir?</i>

257
00:21:42,135 --> 00:21:43,595
Miggs is dead.

258
00:21:44,679 --> 00:21:47,307
Dead? How?

259
00:21:48,308 --> 00:21:51,770
The orderly heard Lecter whispering
to him all afternoon, and Miggs crying.

260
00:21:51,937 --> 00:21:55,524
They found him at bed check.
He'd swallowed his own tongue.

261
00:21:57,442 --> 00:21:58,693
Starling?

262
00:21:59,069 --> 00:22:01,029
Yeah, I'm still here, sir.

263
00:22:01,196 --> 00:22:04,115
I just... I don't know
how to feel about this.

264
00:22:04,574 --> 00:22:08,870
You don't have to feel any way about it.
Lecter did it to amuse himself.

265
00:22:09,329 --> 00:22:11,665
<i>Look, I know it got ugly today,</i>

266
00:22:11,832 --> 00:22:15,085
but you mentioned a name
at the end. Mofet.

267
00:22:15,293 --> 00:22:17,003
Any follow-up on her?

268
00:22:17,796 --> 00:22:20,549
Well, Lecter altered or destroyed
most of his patients' histories

269
00:22:20,715 --> 00:22:23,176
prior to capture, so there's no record
of anyone named Mofet.

270
00:22:23,343 --> 00:22:27,472
But I thought the "yourself" reference

271
00:22:27,639 --> 00:22:29,140
was too hokey for Lecter,

272
00:22:29,307 --> 00:22:33,520
so I figured, he's from Baltimore,
and I looked in the phone book,

273
00:22:33,687 --> 00:22:37,107
and there's a "Your
Self Storage" facility,

274
00:22:37,274 --> 00:22:39,484
<i>right outside of downtown Baltimore, sir.</i>

275
00:22:41,736 --> 00:22:45,532
Unit 31 was leased for 10 years,

276
00:22:45,782 --> 00:22:47,367
prepaid in full.

277
00:22:47,576 --> 00:22:48,827
The contract

278
00:22:48,952 --> 00:22:52,956
is in the name of a Miss Hester Mofet.

279
00:22:53,832 --> 00:22:56,334
So nobody's been in here since 1980?

280
00:22:56,585 --> 00:22:58,378
Not to my knowledge.

281
00:22:59,045 --> 00:23:02,883
Privacy is a great concern
to my customers.

282
00:23:03,508 --> 00:23:05,635
Yes, I won't disturb anything. I promise.

283
00:23:05,802 --> 00:23:08,179
I'll be out of here before you know it.

284
00:23:08,346 --> 00:23:11,892
- Can I help you?
- Yes, actually, you can.

285
00:23:17,022 --> 00:23:18,231
It's stuck.

286
00:23:18,398 --> 00:23:21,067
We could return tomorrow with my son.

287
00:23:21,318 --> 00:23:22,819
What about him?

288
00:23:24,195 --> 00:23:28,909
I would ask my driver to help you,
but he detests physical labor.

289
00:23:29,868 --> 00:23:30,994
Great.

290
00:23:31,578 --> 00:23:34,581
You just stay here.
I'll be back in one minute.

291
00:24:06,821 --> 00:24:08,073
It's stuck.

292
00:24:08,239 --> 00:24:10,283
Hand me that flashlight, sir.

293
00:24:20,961 --> 00:24:22,045
Oh.

294
00:24:23,880 --> 00:24:28,218
If this door should fall down
or anything else,

295
00:24:29,803 --> 00:24:32,597
this is the number
for our Baltimore field office.

296
00:24:32,764 --> 00:24:34,516
Now, they know that you're with me.

297
00:24:34,683 --> 00:24:36,643
You call them if anything should happen.

298
00:24:36,810 --> 00:24:38,395
Yes, Miss Starling.

299
00:27:09,879 --> 00:27:10,880
Clarice...

300
00:27:11,131 --> 00:27:14,092
- They're waiting for you. Watch yourself.
- Thank you.

301
00:27:14,968 --> 00:27:18,304
Hester Mofet.
It's an anagram, isn't it, Doctor?

302
00:27:19,222 --> 00:27:22,475
Hester Mofet, "The rest of me."

303
00:27:22,642 --> 00:27:26,271
"Miss The Rest Of Me,"
meaning that you rented that garage?

304
00:28:02,390 --> 00:28:03,683
Thank you.

305
00:28:04,267 --> 00:28:06,311
Your bleeding has stopped.

306
00:28:08,396 --> 00:28:09,898
How did you...

307
00:28:11,608 --> 00:28:13,026
It's nothing.

308
00:28:13,443 --> 00:28:15,153
It's just a scratch.

309
00:28:16,446 --> 00:28:18,823
Dr. Lecter, whose head is in that bottle?

310
00:28:18,990 --> 00:28:22,076
Why don't you ask me about Buffalo Bill?

311
00:28:22,243 --> 00:28:24,162
Why, do you know something about him?

312
00:28:24,287 --> 00:28:26,331
I might, if I saw the case file.

313
00:28:26,497 --> 00:28:28,333
You could get that for me.

314
00:28:28,499 --> 00:28:30,084
Why don't we talk about Miss Mofet?

315
00:28:30,251 --> 00:28:32,170
You wanted me to find him.

316
00:28:32,545 --> 00:28:35,757
His real name is Benjamin Raspail.

317
00:28:36,299 --> 00:28:38,009
A former patient of mine,

318
00:28:38,176 --> 00:28:42,597
whose romantic attachments ran to,
shall we say, the exotic.

319
00:28:43,264 --> 00:28:44,766
I did not kill him, I assure you.

320
00:28:44,933 --> 00:28:47,518
Merely tucked him away
very much as I found him,

321
00:28:47,685 --> 00:28:50,188
after he'd missed three appointments.

322
00:28:51,356 --> 00:28:53,650
If you didn't kill him, then who did, sir?

323
00:28:53,816 --> 00:28:54,984
Who can say?

324
00:28:55,151 --> 00:28:56,778
Best thing for him, really.

325
00:28:56,945 --> 00:28:59,072
His therapy was going nowhere.

326
00:28:59,822 --> 00:29:02,617
His dress, makeup...

327
00:29:03,326 --> 00:29:05,036
Raspail was a transvestite?

328
00:29:05,203 --> 00:29:07,538
In life? Oh, no.

329
00:29:07,664 --> 00:29:09,916
Garden variety manic-depressive.

330
00:29:10,083 --> 00:29:12,085
Tedious. Very tedious.

331
00:29:12,669 --> 00:29:15,213
And I just think of him
as a kind of experiment,

332
00:29:15,380 --> 00:29:18,716
a fledgling killer's first effort
at transformation.

333
00:29:18,925 --> 00:29:21,636
How did you feel
when you saw him, Clarice?

334
00:29:22,262 --> 00:29:24,138
Scared at first, then,

335
00:29:25,139 --> 00:29:26,516
exhilarated.

336
00:29:27,100 --> 00:29:29,394
Jack Crawford is helping your career,
isn't he?

337
00:29:29,560 --> 00:29:32,605
Apparently, he likes you,
and you like him, too.

338
00:29:32,981 --> 00:29:34,899
I never thought about it.

339
00:29:35,149 --> 00:29:38,069
Do you think Jack Crawford
wants you sexually?

340
00:29:38,236 --> 00:29:39,696
True, he is much older,

341
00:29:39,862 --> 00:29:43,408
but do you think he visualizes
scenarios, exchanges,

342
00:29:43,574 --> 00:29:44,909
fucking you?

343
00:29:47,704 --> 00:29:49,122
That doesn't interest me, Doctor.

344
00:29:49,289 --> 00:29:52,792
Frankly, it's the sort of thing
that Miggs would say.

345
00:29:54,794 --> 00:29:56,170
Not anymore.

346
00:30:03,970 --> 00:30:05,513
Thank you, Barney.

347
00:30:09,517 --> 00:30:11,811
What happened to your drawings?

348
00:30:13,146 --> 00:30:15,440
Punishment, you see, for Miggs.

349
00:30:15,857 --> 00:30:17,734
Just like that gospel program.

350
00:30:17,859 --> 00:30:20,862
When you leave,
they'll turn the volume way up.

351
00:30:21,029 --> 00:30:23,990
Dr. Chilton does enjoy his petty torments.

352
00:30:24,824 --> 00:30:27,660
What did you mean
by transformation, Doctor?

353
00:30:36,294 --> 00:30:39,547
I've been in this room
for eight years now, Clarice.

354
00:30:40,006 --> 00:30:43,468
I know they will never,
ever let me out while I'm alive.

355
00:30:44,260 --> 00:30:46,054
What I want is a view.

356
00:30:46,596 --> 00:30:50,433
I want a window where I can see a tree,
or even water.

357
00:30:50,600 --> 00:30:54,062
I want to be in a federal institution
far away from Dr. Chilton.

358
00:30:54,228 --> 00:30:56,689
What did you mean by fledgling killer?

359
00:30:57,023 --> 00:30:59,025
Are you saying that he's killed again?

360
00:30:59,192 --> 00:31:02,403
I'm offering you a psychological profile
on Buffalo Bill,

361
00:31:02,570 --> 00:31:04,530
based on the case evidence.

362
00:31:10,036 --> 00:31:12,372
I'll help you catch him, Clarice.

363
00:31:19,170 --> 00:31:21,255
You know who he is, don't you?

364
00:31:22,173 --> 00:31:24,926
Tell me who decapitated
your patient, Doctor.

365
00:31:25,093 --> 00:31:27,720
All good things to those who wait.

366
00:31:28,304 --> 00:31:29,514
I've waited, Clarice,

367
00:31:29,680 --> 00:31:32,517
but how long can you
and old Jackie boy wait?

368
00:31:32,934 --> 00:31:34,894
Our little Billy must already be searching

369
00:31:35,061 --> 00:31:38,064
for that next special lady.

370
00:32:41,377 --> 00:32:43,129
Hey, little cheeper.

371
00:32:51,804 --> 00:32:53,514
I'll be right there.

372
00:32:54,307 --> 00:32:55,475
Oh, shoot.

373
00:33:02,523 --> 00:33:03,816
Goddamn it.

374
00:33:12,992 --> 00:33:14,452
Perfect! Jesus.

375
00:33:20,291 --> 00:33:22,001
Can I help you with that?

376
00:33:23,127 --> 00:33:25,171
- Would you?
- Sure.

377
00:33:26,214 --> 00:33:27,882
- Thank you.
- That's all right.

378
00:33:28,049 --> 00:33:30,343
- You look kind of handicapped.
- Yeah.

379
00:33:30,676 --> 00:33:33,638
I got it this far.
I just can't get it up in the truck.

380
00:33:33,804 --> 00:33:35,306
Here. Just grab this.

381
00:33:35,848 --> 00:33:36,807
Okay.

382
00:33:36,974 --> 00:33:39,101
Good. Just set it down. That's good.

383
00:33:39,852 --> 00:33:43,105
Get in the truck.
I want to push it all the way up.

384
00:33:43,856 --> 00:33:45,856
- I really appreciate this. Thank you.
- All right.

385
00:33:45,983 --> 00:33:47,527
- Yeah.
- Thank you.

386
00:33:48,152 --> 00:33:50,071
Just go all the way back.

387
00:33:50,905 --> 00:33:52,740
Okay. Is this good?

388
00:33:52,907 --> 00:33:54,367
Yeah, that's good.

389
00:33:56,202 --> 00:33:58,371
- That's great.
- Okay.

390
00:33:58,871 --> 00:34:01,207
Say, are you about a size 14?

391
00:34:01,499 --> 00:34:02,542
Sorry?

392
00:34:23,938 --> 00:34:24,981
Good.

393
00:34:43,374 --> 00:34:47,086
Oh, good. Good.

394
00:35:03,102 --> 00:35:04,228
Hold!

395
00:35:16,782 --> 00:35:17,992
Starling!

396
00:35:20,745 --> 00:35:22,455
Outside. Let's go.

397
00:35:23,623 --> 00:35:26,500
Cindy, in the ring for Starling. Let's go!

398
00:35:34,925 --> 00:35:36,719
FBI! Hold it! Hold it right there!

399
00:35:36,886 --> 00:35:38,655
Saddle up. Pack your field gear.
You're moving out.

400
00:35:38,679 --> 00:35:40,157
- You're going with Crawford.
- Where?

401
00:35:40,181 --> 00:35:41,861
Found a girl's body down in West Virginia.

402
00:35:42,016 --> 00:35:44,896
Been in the water about a week.
Looks like a Buffalo Bill-type situation.

403
00:35:56,822 --> 00:35:59,867
He keeps them alive for three days.
We don't know why.

404
00:36:00,034 --> 00:36:03,120
There's no evidence
of rape or physical abuse prior to death.

405
00:36:03,287 --> 00:36:06,290
All the mutilation you see there
is postmortem.

406
00:36:06,666 --> 00:36:08,250
Okay, three days.

407
00:36:08,417 --> 00:36:12,046
Then he shoots them, skins them,
and dumps them.

408
00:36:12,338 --> 00:36:14,131
Each body in a different river.

409
00:36:14,298 --> 00:36:17,385
The water leaves us no trace evidence
of any kind.

410
00:36:17,551 --> 00:36:20,054
That's Fredrica Bimmel, the first one.

411
00:36:20,221 --> 00:36:23,140
Her body was the only one
he took the trouble to weight down,

412
00:36:23,307 --> 00:36:26,018
so actually, she was the third girl found.

413
00:36:26,268 --> 00:36:28,104
After her, he got lazy.

414
00:36:30,481 --> 00:36:32,900
Okay. Let's see.

415
00:36:33,567 --> 00:36:35,528
Circles where the girls were abducted,

416
00:36:35,695 --> 00:36:37,905
arrows where their bodies were found.

417
00:36:38,072 --> 00:36:41,158
This new one today washed up here.

418
00:36:41,325 --> 00:36:42,702
Elk River, West Virginia.

419
00:37:02,388 --> 00:37:05,266
Look at him, Starling.
Tell me what you see.

420
00:37:06,225 --> 00:37:07,768
Well, he's a white male.

421
00:37:07,935 --> 00:37:11,480
Serial killers tend to hunt
within their own ethnic groups.

422
00:37:11,647 --> 00:37:12,648
He's not a drifter.

423
00:37:12,815 --> 00:37:16,277
He's got his own house somewhere,
not an apartment.

424
00:37:16,610 --> 00:37:19,613
- Why?
- What he does with them takes privacy.

425
00:37:20,156 --> 00:37:22,116
He's in his 30s or 40s.

426
00:37:22,283 --> 00:37:24,577
He's got real physical strength,

427
00:37:24,785 --> 00:37:27,621
combined with an older man's self-control.

428
00:37:27,788 --> 00:37:29,957
He's cautious, precise.

429
00:37:30,791 --> 00:37:33,627
And he's never impulsive.
He'll never stop.

430
00:37:34,044 --> 00:37:35,254
Why not?

431
00:37:36,922 --> 00:37:40,468
He's got a real taste for it now.
He's getting better at his work.

432
00:37:42,094 --> 00:37:43,804
Not bad, Starling.

433
00:37:43,971 --> 00:37:46,223
- Questions?
- Yes, sir.

434
00:37:47,099 --> 00:37:50,603
You haven't mentioned anything about
the information contained in my report

435
00:37:50,770 --> 00:37:52,813
or Dr. Lecter's offer, sir.

436
00:37:52,980 --> 00:37:54,690
I'm considering it.

437
00:37:54,857 --> 00:37:57,693
That's why you sent me in there, isn't it?

438
00:37:57,860 --> 00:37:59,945
To get his help on Buffalo Bill, sir?

439
00:38:02,990 --> 00:38:05,868
Well, if that was the case, then I just...

440
00:38:06,243 --> 00:38:08,621
I just wish I was in on it. That's all.

441
00:38:08,913 --> 00:38:11,165
If I had sent you in there
with an actual agenda,

442
00:38:11,332 --> 00:38:13,083
Lecter would have known it instantly.

443
00:38:13,250 --> 00:38:16,504
He would have toyed with you,
then turned to stone.

444
00:38:50,204 --> 00:38:53,582
Excuse me.
Sheriff Perkins, these are the FBI people.

445
00:38:53,749 --> 00:38:56,335
Sheriff Perkins. Jack Crawford, FBI.

446
00:38:56,669 --> 00:38:59,213
Special Agent Terry, Agent Starling.

447
00:38:59,463 --> 00:39:01,882
We appreciate being invited
to your jurisdiction.

448
00:39:02,049 --> 00:39:05,219
I didn't call you. That was somebody
from the State Attorney's office.

449
00:39:05,386 --> 00:39:07,471
We'll extend you every courtesy,
but right now...

450
00:39:07,638 --> 00:39:11,976
Sheriff, this type of sex crime
has certain aspects.

451
00:39:12,142 --> 00:39:14,395
I'd just as soon discuss in private.

452
00:39:14,562 --> 00:39:16,313
You know what I mean?

453
00:41:06,966 --> 00:41:09,551
- Oscar, fetch Dr. Akin from the chapel.
- Yes, sir.

454
00:41:09,718 --> 00:41:10,844
Starling, we're back here.

455
00:41:11,011 --> 00:41:14,098
Tell Lamar to come on
when he's finished playing his music.

456
00:41:14,264 --> 00:41:16,809
Yeah. We'll be sending in a minute.

457
00:41:17,559 --> 00:41:18,686
Is this working?

458
00:41:18,852 --> 00:41:21,480
I need a six-way linkup.

459
00:41:21,647 --> 00:41:23,273
Chicago, Detroit...

460
00:41:23,399 --> 00:41:24,775
What? What?

461
00:41:29,989 --> 00:41:32,616
Excuse me! Excuse me, gentlemen.

462
00:41:32,783 --> 00:41:34,952
You officers and gentlemen,
listen here now.

463
00:41:35,119 --> 00:41:36,620
There's things we need to do for her.

464
00:41:36,787 --> 00:41:38,539
I know that you all brought her this far

465
00:41:38,706 --> 00:41:41,291
and that her folks would
thank you if they could

466
00:41:41,458 --> 00:41:43,669
for your kindness and your sensitivity.

467
00:41:43,836 --> 00:41:47,256
And now, please,
go on now and let us take care of her.

468
00:41:47,965 --> 00:41:49,341
Go on, now.

469
00:41:52,386 --> 00:41:53,762
Thank you.

470
00:41:57,474 --> 00:41:58,851
Thank you.

471
00:42:00,602 --> 00:42:02,021
Okay, good.

472
00:42:10,237 --> 00:42:12,948
Yeah, that's right.
West Virginia. Elk River.

473
00:42:13,115 --> 00:42:15,075
Stand by for transmission.

474
00:42:18,954 --> 00:42:20,039
Ray.

475
00:42:32,509 --> 00:42:35,220
Doctor, Lamar, let's take a look at her.

476
00:42:51,737 --> 00:42:53,072
Oh, Jesus.

477
00:43:00,871 --> 00:43:02,414
Okay, Starling.

478
00:43:07,461 --> 00:43:08,587
Bill.

479
00:43:24,645 --> 00:43:29,108
Star-shaped contact entrance wound
over the sternum.

480
00:43:31,360 --> 00:43:33,403
Muzzle stamp at the top.

481
00:43:33,570 --> 00:43:35,948
- Wrongful death.
- "Wrongful death."

482
00:43:36,865 --> 00:43:40,160
She'll have to go
to the state pathologist at Claxton.

483
00:43:40,327 --> 00:43:42,496
Well, I better get back to that service.

484
00:43:42,663 --> 00:43:44,414
Lamar will help you.

485
00:43:44,706 --> 00:43:46,250
Lord Almighty.

486
00:43:50,671 --> 00:43:53,006
What else do you see, Starling?

487
00:43:53,966 --> 00:43:56,301
Well, she's not local.

488
00:43:57,594 --> 00:44:00,722
Her ears are pierced three times,
and there's...

489
00:44:01,974 --> 00:44:05,060
Glitter nail polish.
It looks like town to me.

490
00:44:10,732 --> 00:44:12,359
Two of her fingernails are broken off,

491
00:44:12,526 --> 00:44:16,071
and there's dirt or grit under them.

492
00:44:16,738 --> 00:44:20,242
It looks like she's tried to claw her way
through something.

493
00:44:20,409 --> 00:44:23,209
Ray, get pictures of her teeth.
We'll fax them through Missing Persons.

494
00:44:23,328 --> 00:44:24,454
Right.

495
00:44:34,214 --> 00:44:35,883
Let's do another.

496
00:44:44,683 --> 00:44:47,144
She's got something in her throat.

497
00:44:47,686 --> 00:44:49,521
When a body comes out of the water,

498
00:44:49,688 --> 00:44:52,733
lots of times there's, like,
leaves and things in the mouth.

499
00:45:23,972 --> 00:45:26,767
What is that, some kind of seedpod?

500
00:45:27,559 --> 00:45:30,020
No, sir. That's a bug cocoon.

501
00:45:30,687 --> 00:45:33,482
There's no way that could get
way down in there like that.

502
00:45:33,649 --> 00:45:36,276
Not unless somebody shoved it in there.

503
00:45:38,570 --> 00:45:41,114
She'll be easier to print
when we turn her over.

504
00:45:41,281 --> 00:45:44,534
- Lamar, will you give me a hand with this?
- Yes, sir, I will.

505
00:45:48,330 --> 00:45:51,875
Oh, Jack. What do you make of these?

506
00:45:52,292 --> 00:45:54,336
Different configuration
than the other victims.

507
00:45:54,503 --> 00:45:55,712
Get close-ups.

508
00:45:55,879 --> 00:45:59,424
Victim's skin removed this time
in two large diamond-shaped sections

509
